# Tech Stack

- Language: TypeScript.
- Platform: Visual Studio Code extension (the standard VS Code Extension API).
  The extension must also work in Cursor, which is a VS Code fork - targeting the
  standard API covers both, so do not use anything Cursor-specific.
- Scaffold with the standard tooling (yo code / generator-code) producing a normal
  package.json extension manifest with activation events and contributed commands.
- UI tiles are rendered in a VS Code Webview.
- Node.js APIs (child_process, etc.) are available in the extension host for
  shelling out to tmux and git.
- Target OS: macOS and Linux only. Do not write Windows-specific code; SwarmForge
  depends on tmux.

# Conventions

- Keep the extension-host code and the webview code clearly separated. They are
  different execution contexts that communicate only by message passing
  (postMessage). Do not attempt to share state directly between them.
- The extension host owns all I/O: shelling to tmux, reading .swarmforge/ files,
  running git. The webview is purely presentation plus user input forwarded back
  to the host.
- Prefer small, testable modules. The cleaner agent will improve coverage and
  structure, so write code that is easy to refactor.
- Use clear command IDs namespaced under "swarmforge." (e.g. swarmforge.run,
  swarmforge.stop, swarmforge.setTarget, swarmforge.initTarget).

# Architecture rules (important - these prevent the project going off the rails)

1. Two layers: tile-as-view, tmux-as-substrate.
   - The tiles are TypeScript/webview VIEWS. tmux is the process SUBSTRATE that
     actually runs the agents (SwarmForge's model).
   - These are NOT alternatives - they are different layers. The tile renders and
     forwards input; tmux runs the agents underneath.
   - DO NOT spawn agent processes directly from TypeScript to avoid tmux. That
     would mean reimplementing SwarmForge's orchestration and is explicitly wrong.
     If a task starts to feel like rebuilding process orchestration, stop - that is
     the signal you have crossed this line.

2. Integrate, do not fork.
   - SwarmForge is a pinned, unmodified, separately-installed dependency. Do not
     copy its source into this repo. Interact with it only through:
       - launching its ./swarm wrapper,
       - reading its state under .swarmforge/ (including .swarmforge/tmux-socket),
       - attaching to its tmux sessions/panes,
       - reading its swarmforge.conf to learn the role/window topology.

3. Webview storage restriction.
   - Do NOT use localStorage, sessionStorage, or any browser storage in the webview.
     Keep UI state in memory or persist via the extension host (VS Code workspace
     state / files). Browser storage is not reliable in this context.

4. Secrets.
   - Any tokens or keys (e.g. a GitHub token for opening PRs) live in the extension
     host environment only. Never write them into the target's working directory or
     into any commit.

# Key integration surface to get working first

Before building UI polish, prove these against a real SwarmForge install, in this
order (this is the riskiest part):

1. Launch a swarm against a target path by shelling to ./swarm.
2. Discover SwarmForge's tmux socket (.swarmforge/tmux-socket) and enumerate its
   sessions/windows/panes.
3. Tail one pane's output into a webview tile, live.
4. Send keystrokes INTO a pane (needed for interactive tiles) - this is the
   fiddliest cross-platform piece, so tackle it early.
5. Read .swarmforge/ state to know which stage holds the work.
6. Open a PR from the dev branch into the target's main using git + the GitHub CLI
   or API.

If any of these cannot be done by driving SwarmForge from outside, note it clearly
rather than working around it by modifying SwarmForge - it may be something to
request upstream.
